{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506752","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506752"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:46:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:46:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2566"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2566"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.02,0.04,0.44,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2566"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114512"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2566"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2566"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96513"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"1291"},{"type":"tags","id":"2921"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"6437"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2688"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2699"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27080"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43189"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44586"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48057"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114512"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents due to episodic flank pain on the left side and blood in the urine. She has had these episodic pains for the last year but recently they have started to recur more frequently. She does not smoke or drink. Her father also had a history of recurrent urinary tract infections and died of stroke in his 40s. Temperature is 37 C, blood pressure is 165/100 mm Hg, and pulse is 88/min. Cardiopulmonary examination is normal. Abdominal examination reveals hepatomegaly. A mass is felt in the left flank when the physician performs deep palpation. Serum creatinine is 203 umol/L [53-115]. Urinalysis results are shown below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProtein = Absent\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood = Present\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlucose = Absent\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELeukocyte esterase = Negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENitrites = Negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBacteria = Absent\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWBC = 1-2/hpf\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERBC = 20-30/hpf\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECasts = Absent\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in the management of this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis","Cystoscopy","Renal biopsy","Renal ultrasound","Serum complement levels"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient most likely has \u003Cstrong\u003Eautosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease \u003C/strong\u003E(ADPKD). The autosomal dominant type of polycystic kidney disease usually presents in adulthood (most commonly after 30 years of age). It is characterised by multiple renal cysts of varying sizes. Patients may have renal and extrarenal manifestations. The renal manifestations include flank/abdominal pain, haematuria, recurrent urinary tract infections, and nephrolithiasis. Kidneys may be palpable on deep palpation of the flanks. The extrarenal manifestations include benign hepatic, pancreatic, and splenic cysts. This patient\u2019s hepatomegaly is possibly because of hepatic cysts. Patients may also develop cerebral berry aneurysm. This patient\u2019s father had recurrent urinary tract infection and most likely died from rupture of cerebral berry aneurysm. Patients may also have hypertension. Hypertension in patients aged \u0026lt;35 years raises suspicion for secondary causes of hypertension. The possible explanation for hypertension in ADPKD is that cyst development leads to local ischaemia and a subsequent increase in renin release. Patients who are suspected of ADPKD should undergo \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E which may show multiple variably-sized cysts bilaterally. Hepatic, pancreatic, and/or splenic cysts may also be identified on the ultrasound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan of the abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is usually not indicated as the first-line investigation due to unnecessary radiation exposure. However, it may be performed if the ultrasonography is inconclusive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECystoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate for the diagnosis of bladder cancer which also presents with gross haematuria. However, bladder cancer is not associated with hypertension and hepatomegaly. In addition, bladder cancer is usually seen in chronic smokers. This patient does not smoke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary as the diagnosis can be made with clinical history and ultrasound. It may be performed in patients with glomerulonephritis which also presents with haematuria. However, it is also associated with RBC casts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum complement levels\u003C/strong\u003E may be performed in patients with autoimmune nephritis (eg, lupus nephritis, post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis). This patient\u2019s clinical history and urinalysis make the diagnosis of ADPKD more likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease (ADPKD) usually presents in adulthood (most commonly after 30 years of age) and is characterised by multiple renal cysts of varying sizes.","Renal ultrasound is the first-line investigation for suspected autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease (ADPKD) as it can identify multiple renal cysts without radiation exposure."],"references":["Bergmann C, Guay-Woodford LM, Harris PC, Horie S, Peters DJM, Torres VE. Polycystic kidney disease. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2018 Dec 6;4(1):50. doi: 10.1038/s41572-018-0047-y. PMID: 30523303; PMCID: PMC6592047. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30523303/","Chapman AB, Wei W. Imaging approaches to patients with polycystic kidney disease. Semin Nephrol. 2011 May;31(3):237-44. doi: 10.1016/j.semnephrol.2011.05.003. PMID: 21784272; PMCID: PMC3143364. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3143364/","Pei Y, Obaji J, Dupuis A, Paterson AD, Magistroni R, Dicks E, Parfrey P, Cramer B, Coto E, Torra R, San Millan JL, Gibson R, Breuning M, Peters D, Ravine D. Unified criteria for ultrasonographic diagnosis of ADPKD. J Am Soc Nephrol. 2009 Jan;20(1):205-12. doi: 10.1681/ASN.2008050507. Epub 2008 Oct 22. PMID: 18945943; PMCID: PMC2615723. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2615723/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96513"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2566"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96513"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-17T10:22:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-17T10:24:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2566"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114512"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"hea